This paper is about sentiment classification, which is a common topic in natural language processing (NLP). The use of RNN and CNN models also suggests that it belongs to the sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). Additionally, the focus on target-oriented sentiment classification suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of information retrieval (cs.IR), as this task is often used in opinion mining and sentiment analysis for product reviews. The use of attention mechanisms and the proposal of a new model also suggest that it may belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the use of benchmarks and experiments suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE).
